<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="89" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d89">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 151.096/28.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-04">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 4, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I am requested by the Minister for Foreign Affairs to instruct certain
                            consuls to visa Section 6 certificates issued by local provisional
                            government. Would compliance with this request involve recognition of
                            the present administration?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Calhoun</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>